## 2. Structured Code Review

### Review Matrix

| Category | Strength | Improvement Suggestion |
|----------|----------|------------------------|
| **A. Correctness** | Recurrence auto-creation works correctly for weekly, monthly, and yearly rules using `date-fns`. | `completeItem` marks the item completed before attempting the recurrence insert — no transaction means no rollback on failure. |
| **B. Architecture** | Clean separation between controller, service, and repository. Controllers contain no query logic; repositories contain no business rules. | Filter/sort logic in `itemRepository.getAll()` is 40+ lines of inline conditionals — hard to test in isolation and hard to extend. |
| **C. Readability** | Naming is consistent and intention-revealing throughout (`completeItem`, `deleteItem`, `createItem`). TypeScript interfaces are used for all item shapes. | `validate.ts` uses nested if-else blocks for each field. A schema library like Zod would be more declarative and less error-prone. |
| **D. Security** | All routes are protected by JWT middleware. `userId` is sourced from the decoded token, not the request body, preventing spoofing. | `DELETE` and `PUT` handlers have no ownership check — any authenticated user can modify or delete any item by ID (IDOR vulnerability). |
| **E. Performance** | All filters apply at the query level via Knex `.where()` — no post-fetch filtering in application memory. | No pagination on `GET /api/items` — all matching items are returned in a single response regardless of count. |

