## 3. Reflection

**What issues were discovered during the review?**

Six issues were identified across the five reviewed files. The two highest severity were the IDOR vulnerability on the DELETE and PUT endpoints — where authentication was present but authorization was completely absent — and the missing database transaction on `completeItem`, which creates an unrecoverable data loss scenario when the recurrence insert fails. Three medium issues addressed the untestable inline filter chain, the broken ISO date regex, and absent pagination on the list endpoint. One low severity issue flagged that recurrence rule strings are scattered across multiple layers with no shared constant, creating a silent failure mode if any label ever changes.

None of the issues would have been caught by TypeScript alone. They were logic-layer and query-level problems — the code compiled and passed single-user testing without any indication of the gaps.

**Were any architectural inconsistencies identified?**

Yes. The primary inconsistency was the 40-line inline filter-building block inside `itemRepository.getAll()`. The repository layer is intended to be a thin data-access wrapper over Knex, but this function became a logic-heavy module that cannot be independently tested and grows harder to maintain with each new filter parameter. A secondary inconsistency is that `validate.ts` enforces business rules — checking that `recurrence_rule` is a valid enum value — rather than just structural validation. Business rules belong in the service layer. If the allowed recurrence rules change, both files must be updated with no compiler enforcement linking them.

**What would have happened if this code were merged without review?**

The IDOR vulnerability would have shipped to production silently. Single-user testing never exposes it because the developer always tests with their own account, meaning the ownership check never fails. The bug only surfaces when a second user account exists and cross-account access is tested deliberately, which rarely happens without a formal review pass. The missing transaction on `completeItem` would have been similarly invisible in development — it only fails under transient database conditions that eventually occur in production, at which point users would find recurring tasks silently disappearing after completion with no error to debug against. The absent pagination would have appeared gradually as a performance regression rather than an immediate failure, the kind of problem attributed to the app getting slower rather than identified as a missing feature.

**How will code reviews be integrated into future sprints?**

Pull requests will be required for all feature branches with no direct pushes to main. Authorization scoping — verifying that the authenticated user owns the resource being accessed — will be added as an explicit required checklist item for any endpoint that accepts a resource ID in the URL. Database handlers performing more than one write will be required to use transactions, enforced through a prompt in the PR template. Pagination will be implemented as a standard pattern on all list endpoints before Sprint 2 begins rather than retrofitted later. Zod will be adopted for all new validation middleware going forward, with the existing `validate.ts` migrated incrementally.
